I had read a review of the (maracucha) burger, which was what brought me here, but honestly it was pretty disappointing. The meat was like a hockey puck (I genuinely had difficulty cutting it with the plastic knife), and the bun was almost non-existent on the bottom making it impossible to pick up and eat like a regular burger. However, the mozzarella & salami cachapa saved the day. It was truly delicious and would be something to come back for. Overall, it was solid, not great, and I'd give it another star if it wasn't so wasteful regarding plastic; everything served here is disposable, even if you're dining in. Time to get with the 21st century and stop filling landfills with single-use trash.

VENEZEULA 🇻🇪 Eat the World NYC review: The junk foods of Venezuela always seem to have a long layover in the Dominican Republic before they find their way to New York City. At Tu Cachapa in Washington Heights this is perhaps more obvious than anywhere, with yaroa beside all the street food classics of Venezuela. This makes sense in this neighborhood which probably has 100 Dominicans for every person from Venezuela, but either way these two countries must be junk food soulmates from former lives.

Easily some of the best food I’ve had in New York. It’s a small spot with a few chairs and a counter for a handfuls of people to dine in so it’s not meant to accommodate a large crowd, nor is your food coming out on fine plating, this is a comfort food, grab and go kind of spot. The food was extremely tasty, I ordered a chicken arepa and something else I can’t recall the name of but my God, it was extremely fulfilling. Prices are super reasonable as well even though I live in Brooklyn, I’ll absolutely be making trips uptown to grab a bite throughout summer.
